Awesome Jonny!

I also wrote the additional extension properties to provide more useful stuff!


  public int Total { get; set; }
  public bool IsFirst { get { return this.Index == 0; } }
  public bool IsLast { get { return this.Index == this.Total - 1; } }
  public bool IsEven { get { return this.Index % 2 == 0; } }
  public bool IsOdd { get { return this.Index % 2 != 0; } }

item.content:encoded:
I recently answered <a href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/4410282/how-can-i-prevent-button-mashing-when-using-anchors-instead-of-buttons/">this question on StackOverflow</a> asking how to prevent someone from clicking a link multiple times.

This is the solution I came up with:

[js]$(&quot;a&quot;).click(function(e) {
    e.preventDefault();

    if (!$(this).data('isClicked')) {
        var link = $(this);

        // Your code on successful click

        // Set the isClicked value and set a timer to reset in 3s
        link.data('isClicked', true);
        setTimeout(function() {
            link.removeData('isClicked')
        }, 3000);
    } else {
        // Anything you want to say 'Bad user!'
    }
});[/js]

You can use <a href="http://api.jquery.com/category/miscellaneous/data-storage/">jQuery's data storage</a> methods to assign arbitrary bits of data to specific DOM elements. In this case, when the user clicks a link I assign a property to the element as well as setting a timer to remove it 3 seconds later. This lets me know if the specific element has already been clicked by just calling the <code>data</code> method.

It's not a bullet proof solution since it's incredibly easy to get around if you're determined enough. However, it is a simple example of how you can use those methods.

